\section PydanticSpecOverview Overview

The authoritative statement of %Dakota input grammar now lives in the
Pydantic models under \c dakota/python/dakota/spec.  In practice, this
means that developers should start grammar changes in the Python models
and supporting validation helpers rather than treating \c dakota.xml as
the primary source of truth.

For general background on Pydantic itself, see the official
\htmlonly
<a href="https://pydantic.dev/docs/validation/latest/get-started/">Pydantic documentation</a>
\endhtmlonly
documentation.

Most grammar models inherit from \c DakotaBaseModel in
\c dakota/python/dakota/spec/base.py.

In this documentation:

<ul>
<li>A parsed field is a class attribute that corresponds directly to
    user input.  These are the keywords, flags, arguments, and nested
    blocks that the parser accepts from a %Dakota input specification.
    Parsed fields are declared with \c DakotaField.</li>
<li>A validation rule is logic that checks relationships among multiple
    parsed fields or fills one field from information in others.  Typical
    examples are "this list must have length \c count", "lower bounds must
    be below upper bounds", or "if the user omitted initial_point, derive
    it from bounds".</li>
<li>A computed field is a derived value that is not supplied by the user
    as input, but is computed from validated parsed fields and exported in
    schema or model output.  Typical examples are inferred lower and upper
    bounds for variable types whose bounds come from distribution
    parameters.</li>
</ul>

The common split of responsibilities is:

<ul>
<li>Use \c DakotaField for values the user can write in the grammar.</li>
<li>Use \c ValidationRule subclasses for checks or mutations that depend
    on more than one parsed field.</li>
<li>Use \c ComputedFieldSpec plus \c @computed_field for values that are
    derived after parsing and should appear in exported schema as computed
    outputs rather than user-provided inputs.</li>
</ul>


\section PydanticSpecUnions How Union Fields Are Processed

\c DakotaBaseModel applies a model-level validator before normal Pydantic
validation to enforce %Dakota's one-of semantics for Union fields.  This
logic lives in \c DakotaBaseModel._validate_union_fields in
\c dakota/python/dakota/spec/base.py.

The Union handling logic expects branch models to be single-key wrapper
models.  The wrapper field name is the discriminator.  For example, in a
field such as
\code
trend: Union[TrendNone, ExperimentalGPTrendConstant, ExperimentalGPTrendLinear]
\endcode
the accepted user input is a dictionary with exactly one key, such as
\c {"linear": {...}} or \c {"none": true}, depending on the wrapped model.

The \c dakota metadata key \c union_pattern is exported to schema as
\c x-union-pattern.  This metadata is important because %Dakota uses six
distinct Union patterns to represent the different semantics that used to
come from XML \c oneOf groups.  The pattern number does not itself drive
branch selection at runtime, but it records the intended grammar semantics
and should match the Python type shape.

The current patterns are:

<ul>
<li>Pattern 1: optional field with a model default.
    Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,OptionB,...] with a model
    \c default_factory.
    Use this when omitting the field should enable a sensible default
    branch automatically.</li>
<li>Pattern 2: optional field with no default branch.
    Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,OptionB,...] | None with
    \c default=None.
    Use this when omission means the feature is disabled.</li>
<li>Pattern 3: three-state optional field with a default branch.
    Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,OptionB,...,dict] | None with a model
    \c default_factory.
    Use this when omission means disabled, \c {} means enabled with
    default configuration, and a branch object means enabled with explicit
    configuration.</li>
<li>Pattern 4: required Union.
    Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,OptionB,...].
    Use this when the user must choose a branch explicitly.</li>
<li>Pattern 5: three-state optional field without a grammar-level default.
    Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,OptionB,...,dict] | None with
    \c default=None.
    Use this when omission means disabled, \c {} means "enable with
    implementation defaults", and a branch object means explicit
    configuration.</li>
<li>Pattern 6: required field whose branch selection is optional.
    Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,OptionB,...,dict].
    Use this when the parent block must exist, but an empty object is a
    valid "no subselection" choice.</li>
</ul>

Runtime validation behavior is:

<ul>
<li>If the Union contains more than one model branch, exactly one branch
    must be selected.</li>
<li>If the field value is already a validated model instance, it is
    accepted as long as it matches one of the Union branches.</li>
<li>If the value is a dictionary with more than one key, validation
    fails.</li>
<li>If the key does not match one of the registered single-field branch
    models, validation fails.</li>
<li>If the Union effectively has only one model branch, the field is
    treated like a normal field and Pydantic handles it directly.</li>
<li>If \c dict is one of the Union branches, an empty dictionary may be
    meaningful and is handled specially for Patterns 3, 5, and 6.</li>
<li>For Pattern 3 specifically, omission is converted to \c None while
    \c {} instantiates the model from \c default_factory.  This is the
    mechanism that preserves the three distinct states.</li>
</ul>

When updating a Union field, consult the developer guide in
\c /workspace/pydantic_patterns_developer_guide.md and make sure the
Python type annotation, \c default or \c default_factory, and
\c union_pattern metadata all describe the same one-of semantics.


\section PydanticSpecDakotaField DakotaField Authoring

\c DakotaField is a small wrapper around \c pydantic.Field.  All ordinary
Pydantic field arguments still work, including \c default,
\c default_factory, \c description, numeric bounds such as \c gt or
\c ge, and any other keyword supported by \c Field.

The \c dakota dictionary argument controls parser and IR behavior
associated with the field.

The most commonly used authoring keys are:

<ul>
<li>\c aliases</li>
<li>\c block_pointer</li>
<li>\c argument</li>
<li>\c anchor</li>
<li>\c union_pattern</li>
<li>\c model_default</li>
<li>\c internal_only</li>
<li>\c materialization</li>
</ul>

\subsection PydanticSpecDakotaAliases aliases

\c aliases defines alternate keyword spellings that are accepted in
%Dakota's freeform input.

It takes either:

<ul>
<li>a list of strings, which is the normal pattern, or</li>
<li>a single string, which the parser generator also accepts.</li>
</ul>

Example:
\code
directory_tag: Literal[True] | None = DakotaField(
    default=None,
    description="Tag evaluation directories with identifiers",
    dakota={"aliases": ["dir_tag"]},
)
\endcode

Use \c aliases when an existing Dakota synonym should remain legal input.
Do not use it to invent a second preferred spelling without a backward
compatibility reason.

\subsection PydanticSpecDakotaBlockPointer block_pointer

\c block_pointer marks a field as a block pointer rather than an ordinary
value-bearing keyword.  In parser terms, this means the keyword points at
another named block or context instead of introducing a normal scalar or
list parameter.

It takes a string target naming the referenced block family or block role.
In the current models this is written as values such as \c "method".
The parser generator records this as a \c block_pointer constraint on the
generated keyword metadata.

Use \c block_pointer only when the user input names another block by
pointer-like reference semantics.  It is not a general-purpose nested model
marker.

\subsection PydanticSpecDakotaArgument argument

\c argument identifies the nested field that should be treated as the
inline parameter for a keyword.  This is how the parser generator knows
which child field acts like the keyword's argument instead of an ordinary
sub-keyword.

It takes a string naming one child field in the referenced config model.
Common values in the current models include \c "count", \c "filename",
\c "drivers", \c "flags", \c "order", and \c "level".

When present, the parser generator resolves the nested config and treats the
named child as the parameter slot for the enclosing keyword.

\subsection PydanticSpecDakotaAnchor anchor

\c anchor marks a Union-like field whose discriminator branches should be
attached directly to the parent keyword context instead of beneath a
non-anchor selector keyword.

It takes the boolean value \c True.  Omit the key entirely when the field is
not anchored.

This matters for parser generation because anchored and non-anchored one-of
groups produce different keyword paths in freeform Dakota input.

\subsection PydanticSpecDakotaUnionMeta union_pattern and model_default

\c union_pattern records which of Dakota's six one-of patterns a field is
using.  It takes an integer pattern number.

\c model_default records the default branch name for patterns that have one.
It takes a string naming the chosen model class or branch model.

These two settings should agree with the Python type annotation and
\c default or \c default_factory.  If they drift apart, the schema,
parser-generation logic, and runtime semantics become inconsistent.

\subsection PydanticSpecDakotaInternal internal_only

\c internal_only marks a field as unavailable to user input even though it
exists on the Python model.

It takes a boolean, typically \c True.  \c DakotaBaseModel rejects user
data for such fields during model validation.

A typical field looks like:
\code
solution_target: DakotaFloat = DakotaField(
    default=-DBL_MAX,
    description="Stopping criteria based on objective function value",
    dakota={
        "aliases": ["solution_accuracy"],
        "materialization": [
            {
                "ir_key": "method.solution_target",
                "storage_type": "DIRECT_VALUE",
                "ir_value_type": "Real",
            }
        ],
    },
)
\endcode


\section PydanticSpecMaterialization Materialization and IR Writes

Materialization is the process that takes validated JSON produced from the
Pydantic models and writes the corresponding values into Dakota's
intermediate representation (IR), which is the runtime state later read
through \c ProblemDescDB.

In developer terms:

<ul>
<li>the Pydantic model describes what input is valid,</li>
<li>\c dakota["materialization"] describes how valid input should affect
    IR keys, and</li>
<li>the IR generation and materialization code turns those instructions into
    runtime writes.</li>
</ul>

The high-level pipeline is:

<ol>
<li>Pydantic models emit JSON schema with \c x-materialization metadata.</li>
<li>IR code-generation scripts under \c dakota/src/ir_codegen read that
    schema and derive generated IR contracts and write tables.</li>
<li>At runtime, validated JSON input is traversed by keyword path.</li>
<li>The generated write instructions populate IR keys such as
    \c method.algorithm or \c variables.continuous_design.</li>
</ol>

The two most relevant scripts for understanding this are:

<ul>
<li>\c dakota/src/ir_codegen/extract_defaults_from_schema.py, which extracts
    IR default candidates from schema defaults and \c x-model-default, and</li>
<li>\c dakota/src/ir_codegen/generate_ir_tables.py, which generates
    block-specific IR contracts and write-instruction tables from the
    schema metadata.</li>
</ul>

\subsection PydanticSpecMaterializationShape The materialization field

\c materialization takes a list of dictionaries.  Each dictionary describes
one IR write or presence effect associated with the field.

Common entries in a materialization item include:

<ul>
<li>\c ir_key: destination IR key, such as \c method.solution_target</li>
<li>\c storage_type: how the write should be interpreted</li>
<li>\c ir_value_type: Dakota IR type, such as \c Real, \c size_t,
    \c StringArray, or \c unsigned\ short</li>
<li>\c stored_value: a literal value for presence-driven writes</li>
</ul>

Many fields have exactly one materialization item, but some fan out to
multiple IR keys.  For example, a count field may update both a specific
category total and one or more aggregate totals.

\subsection PydanticSpecMaterializationStorage Permitted storage types

The current models use the following \c storage_type values:

<ul>
<li>\c DIRECT_VALUE: write the field's value directly to the target IR key.</li>
<li>\c ADD_TO_VALUE: add the field's value into the target IR key instead of
    replacing it.  This is commonly used for roll-up counters.</li>
<li>\c PRESENCE_TRUE: field presence writes boolean true.</li>
<li>\c PRESENCE_FALSE: field presence writes boolean false.</li>
<li>\c PRESENCE_LITERAL: field presence writes the supplied
    \c stored_value literal.</li>
<li>\c PRESENCE_ENUM: field presence selects an enumerated stored value.</li>
<li>\c AUGMENT_ENUM: field presence augments an enum-like IR setting with a
    stored symbolic value.</li>
<li>\c TYPE_DATA_COMBINED: a combined handler that writes both a fixed
    literal selection and a direct argument value, potentially to different
    IR keys.</li>
<li>\c METHOD_PIECEWISE: a special combined handler for Dakota's piecewise
    method semantics that expands into more primitive IR writes during code
    generation.</li>
<li>\c ANALYSIS_COMPONENTS: custom handling for interface analysis component
    data.</li>
<li>\c ADJACENCY_MATRIX: custom handling for categorical adjacency-matrix
    data.</li>
<li>\c CATEGORICAL: custom handling for categorical flags or categorical
    metadata.</li>
<li>\c CONTINUOUS_INTERVAL_UNCERTAIN: custom handling for continuous
    interval-uncertain variable data.</li>
<li>\c DISCRETE_INTERVAL_UNCERTAIN: custom handling for discrete
    interval-uncertain variable data.</li>
<li>\c DISCRETE_SET_VALUES: custom handling for discrete set-valued
    variables.</li>
<li>\c DISCRETE_UNCERTAIN_SET_VALUES_PROBS: custom handling for discrete
    uncertain set values together with their probabilities.</li>
<li>\c HISTOGRAM_BIN_UNCERTAIN: custom handling for histogram-bin uncertain
    variables.</li>
<li>\c HISTOGRAM_POINT_UNCERTAIN: custom handling for histogram-point
    uncertain variables.</li>
<li>\c ID_TO_INDEX_SET: custom handling for ID-to-index-set mappings.</li>
<li>\c INT_SET: custom handling for integer-set data.</li>
<li>\c RESPONSE_LEVELS_ARRAY: custom handling for response-level arrays.</li>
<li>\c UNCERTAIN_CORRELATION_MATRIX: custom handling for uncertain
    correlation matrices.</li>
<li>\c UNCERTAIN_INIT_POINT_FLAG: custom handling for uncertain-variable
    initialization-point flags.</li>
</ul>

The first group above are general-purpose write modes.  The remaining names
identify specialized handlers for particular Dakota data shapes.  When
editing existing grammar, prefer to match an existing storage type already
used for the same kind of IR effect instead of inventing a new one casually.

\subsection PydanticSpecMaterializationRequirements Required properties by storage type

Every materialization item should define at least:

<ul>
<li>\c ir_key</li>
<li>\c storage_type</li>
<li>\c ir_value_type</li>
</ul>

In addition, some storage types require extra properties:

<ul>
<li>\c PRESENCE_LITERAL, \c PRESENCE_ENUM, and \c AUGMENT_ENUM require
    \c stored_value, because presence alone is not enough to determine what
    literal should be written.</li>
<li>If a stored literal names a C++ enum constant that needs qualification,
    include \c enum_scope as well.</li>
<li>\c TYPE_DATA_COMBINED requires both a primary literal write and a
    secondary direct-value write.  In practice this means:
    \c stored_value, \c secondary_ir_key, and
    \c secondary_ir_value_type in addition to the primary
    \c ir_key/\c ir_value_type pair.</li>
<li>\c METHOD_PIECEWISE is also a composite handler.  It requires a primary
    literal write and a secondary literal write.  In practice this means:
    \c stored_value, \c secondary_ir_key, \c secondary_ir_value_type, and
    usually \c secondary_literal_value.</li>
</ul>

Concrete \c TYPE_DATA_COMBINED example:
\code
{
    "ir_key": "method.replacement_type",
    "storage_type": "TYPE_DATA_COMBINED",
    "stored_value": "below_limit",
    "secondary_ir_key": "method.jega.fitness_limit",
    "secondary_ir_value_type": "Real",
    "ir_value_type": "String",
}
\endcode

Concrete \c METHOD_PIECEWISE example:
\code
{
    "ir_key": "method.nond.expansion_type",
    "storage_type": "METHOD_PIECEWISE",
    "stored_value": "STD_UNIFORM_U",
    "secondary_ir_key": "method.nond.piecewise_basis",
    "secondary_ir_value_type": "bool",
    "secondary_literal_value": True,
    "ir_value_type": "short",
}
\endcode

For the specialized domain-specific handlers such as
\c HISTOGRAM_POINT_UNCERTAIN or \c UNCERTAIN_CORRELATION_MATRIX, the best
guide is an existing model that already uses that handler.  Those storage
types carry handler-specific expectations beyond the generic
\c ir_key/\c ir_value_type shape.

\subsection PydanticSpecMaterializationAuthoring Authoring guidance

When adding or modifying grammar:

<ol>
<li>Start by deciding which IR key or keys should change when the field is
    present or given a value.</li>
<li>Choose a \c storage_type that matches the desired behavior.  Some
    writes transfer the field value directly, some are presence-driven and
    use \c stored_value, and some invoke a specialized handler for a known
    Dakota data shape.</li>
<li>Set \c ir_value_type to the runtime IR type expected by the generated
    tables and downstream \c ProblemDescDB accessors.</li>
<li>If the field contributes to more than one IR concept, add multiple
    materialization items in the list.</li>
<li>After changing materialization, review the generated IR outputs or
    regeneration diffs to confirm that the expected IR key contracts and
    defaults were produced.</li>
</ol>

Materialization is a large topic and this page only introduces the authoring
surface.  For implementation details, consult the IR generation scripts in
\c dakota/src/ir_codegen and the existing materialization patterns in
\c dakota/python/dakota/spec.


\section PydanticSpecIrDefaults IR Default Values

IR keys need defaults even when the user does not provide a corresponding
input field.  Those defaults are assembled during IR code generation from
three sources:

<ol>
<li>schema-extracted defaults in
    \c dakota/src/schema_defaults_extracted.json</li>
<li>explicit override defaults in
    \c dakota/src/default_overrides_registry.json</li>
<li>type-policy defaults in
    \c dakota/src/default_policy_registry.json</li>
</ol>

The script \c dakota/src/ir_codegen/generate_ir_tables.py reads those three
inputs using \c load_schema_defaults(), \c load_overrides(), and
\c load_policies().  It then merges them into the IR contracts used to
generate the per-block tables.

\subsection PydanticSpecIrDefaultsSchema Schema-extracted defaults

\c schema_defaults_extracted.json contains defaults inferred from the
generated JSON schema.  These come primarily from:

<ul>
<li>field-level Pydantic defaults on schema nodes that carry
    \c x-materialization, and</li>
<li>Union defaults expressed through \c x-model-default.</li>
</ul>

When a default naturally belongs to the grammar model itself, this is the
preferred source.  In practice, that means you should first ask whether the
default should be represented directly in the Pydantic model using
\c default, \c default_factory, or a default Union branch.

\subsection PydanticSpecIrDefaultsOverrides Override defaults

\c default_overrides_registry.json is for IR defaults that cannot or should
not be derived from the schema alone.

Use an override entry when:

<ul>
<li>the IR key needs a default even though no schema field provides one,</li>
<li>the desired IR default is an implementation default rather than a
    grammar-level default, or</li>
<li>the schema-derived default would not faithfully represent Dakota's
    runtime behavior.</li>
</ul>

Entries are grouped by block and provide a key, value type, and explicit
value.

\subsection PydanticSpecIrDefaultsPolicy Policy defaults

\c default_policy_registry.json lists IR keys whose defaults can be assigned
purely from type policy instead of from an explicit value.  For example,
the generator can infer defaults such as false for booleans, 0 for integral
types, 0.0 for floating-point types, and empty string or empty container
values for string or collection types.

Use the policy registry when an IR key should receive the standard default
for its runtime type and does not need a domain-specific override value.

\subsection PydanticSpecIrDefaultsAuthoring Authoring guidance

When you add a new IR key or change materialization, review whether that key
also needs a default contract:

<ol>
<li>If the default is a real grammar default, put it in the Pydantic model
    so it flows into schema extraction.</li>
<li>If the default is implementation-specific and not expressible cleanly in
    schema, add it to \c default_overrides_registry.json.</li>
<li>If the key should simply use the type's ordinary zero/false/empty
    default, add it to \c default_policy_registry.json.</li>
</ol>

The generator expects these sources to be disjoint.  If the same IR key is
claimed by more than one source, \c generate_ir_tables.py treats that as a
collision and raises an error instead of picking a winner silently.


\section PydanticSpecAddModel Adding a New Method or Model

When adding a new grammar node, prefer to follow the existing paired
config-class and selection-wrapper pattern.

\subsection PydanticSpecAddMethod Adding a new method

For a new method:

<ol>
<li>Create a new module in \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/method.</li>
<li>Define a config class for the method body.  Reuse existing mixins
    when they already represent shared syntax.</li>
<li>Make each parsed keyword a typed class attribute using
    \c DakotaField.</li>
<li>Define a matching selection wrapper that inherits from
    \c MethodSelection and contains exactly one field.  That field name
    must be the user-visible method keyword.</li>
<li>Import the new config and selection classes in
    \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/method/__init__.py so they are part of
    \c MethodUnion.</li>
</ol>

Minimal pattern:
\code
class MyMethodConfig(DakotaBaseModel):
    max_iterations: int | None = DakotaField(default=None, description="...")


class MyMethodSelection(MethodSelection):
    my_method: MyMethodConfig = DakotaField(...)
\endcode

The \c MethodSelection registry is populated from subclasses with exactly
one field, and \c MethodUnion is built from that registry.  Top-level
\c DakotaStudy input can then accept either wrapped dictionaries,
selection-wrapper instances, or bare config instances.

\subsection PydanticSpecAddModelNode Adding a new model selection

The model side follows the same pattern using \c ModelSelection in
\c dakota/python/dakota/spec/model.py: create a config class for the
content, create a single-field selection wrapper, and ensure the new
selection is imported where \c ModelUnion is assembled.


\section PydanticSpecValidation Adding Validation Rules and Computed Fields

\subsection PydanticSpecValidators Adding a validation rule

Use a validation rule when correctness depends on multiple fields, when a
field needs a default derived from other fields, or when validation must
mutate related fields in a controlled way.

Validation rules in %Dakota are not Python-only helpers.  They are part
of the shared grammar/validation contract and must be implemented in the
C++ backend as well.  The Python \c ValidationRule class is the schema and
dispatch layer; the authoritative execution logic lives in the
\c dakota_validation_cpp module built from
\c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation.

To add a new rule:

<ol>
<li>Create a subclass of \c ValidationRule, usually in
    \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/validation/rules.py or
    \c variable_rules.py.</li>
<li>Call \c super().__init__ with the rule name, context, referenced
    fields, literals, and error message.</li>
<li>Implement \c __call__(self, instance) so it dispatches to the C++
    backend using the existing \c _call_cpp_validator pattern.</li>
<li>Add the C++ declaration in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/include/dakota/validation.hpp
    or, for variable-specific validators, the appropriate validation
    header.</li>
<li>Add the C++ implementation in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/src/dakota_validation.cpp
    or the appropriate variable-validator source file.</li>
<li>Register the rule name in \c ValidatorRegistry::ValidatorRegistry() in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/src/dakota_validation.cpp.
    The registered string must match the Python \c rule_name exported in
    schema.</li>
<li>Expose the C++ function through the pybind module in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/src/bindings.cpp using
    \c m.def(...).</li>
<li>Add or update C++ tests in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/test/test_validation.cpp.</li>
<li>Attach the rule to the model by declaring
    \c _VALIDATION_RULES: ClassVar[List[ValidationRule]].</li>
</ol>

Example attachment pattern:
\code
class ContinuousDesign(DakotaBaseModel):
    _VALIDATION_RULES: ClassVar[List[ValidationRule]] = [
        CompareLength(
            context="continuous_design",
            list_field="initial_point",
            target_field="count",
        ),
    ]
\endcode

Any model that declares \c _VALIDATION_RULES is automatically wired up by
\c DakotaBaseModel.__init_subclass__:

<ul>
<li>the rules run after model construction, and</li>
<li>their schema metadata is exported in \c x-model-validations.</li>
</ul>

The validator call contract is standardized across Python and C++:

<ul>
<li>\c instance: the current model serialized to a Python/C++ dictionary</li>
<li>\c fields: field paths from \c validationFields</li>
<li>\c literals: literal values from \c validationLiterals</li>
<li>\c context: a descriptive context string for messages</li>
<li>return value: a dictionary of mutations to merge into the instance, or
    an empty dictionary if the rule is check-only</li>
</ul>

\subsection PydanticSpecComputed Adding a computed field

Use a computed field when a value is derived from parsed input and should
appear in schema or in the validated model, but should not be supplied by
the user as input.

Computed fields also require both Python and C++ support.  The Python
property and \c ComputedFieldSpec describe the field to Pydantic and schema
generation, but the function name in \c ComputedFieldSpec(function=...)
must resolve through the shared C++ computed-field registry in
\c dakota_validation_cpp.

The current pattern has two pieces:

<ol>
<li>Declare \c _COMPUTED_FIELDS: ClassVar[dict[str, ComputedFieldSpec]]
    on the model so schema generation knows the field name, description,
    return type, and optional materialization metadata.</li>
<li>Add the matching \c @computed_field property that computes the value.</li>
</ol>

To add a new computed field end to end:

<ol>
<li>Add the \c ComputedFieldSpec entry and matching \c @computed_field
    property on the Python model.</li>
<li>If needed, add a small helper method in
    \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/validation/computed_fields.py that calls
    the backend and optionally mirrors the logic in pure Python.</li>
<li>Add the C++ declaration in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/include/dakota/computed_fields.hpp.</li>
<li>Add the C++ implementation in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/src/dakota_computed_fields.cpp.</li>
<li>Register the function name in
    \c ComputedFieldRegistry::ComputedFieldRegistry() in that same source
    file.  The registered string must match
    \c ComputedFieldSpec(function=...).</li>
<li>Ensure the pybind layer in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/src/bindings.cpp can reach
    the function through \c ComputedFieldRegistry::compute().</li>
<li>Add or update C++ tests in
    \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/test/test_validation.cpp.</li>
</ol>

Example:
\code
_COMPUTED_FIELDS: ClassVar[dict[str, ComputedFieldSpec]] = {
    "lower_bounds": ComputedFieldSpec(
        function="discrete_set_str_lower_bounds",
        description="Lower bounds: min element per variable",
        return_type=list[str],
    ),
}

@computed_field
@property
def lower_bounds(self) -> List[str]:
    return DiscreteSetStrBounds.lower_bounds(self)
\endcode

As with validation rules, \c DakotaBaseModel.__init_subclass__ detects
\c _COMPUTED_FIELDS automatically and exports them in the model schema
under \c x-computed-fields.

In other words, the Python property name, the
\c ComputedFieldSpec(function="...") string, and the C++ registry entry
must all stay in sync.


\section PydanticSpecFloat DakotaFloat

Use \c DakotaFloat instead of plain \c float for grammar fields that may
legitimately carry non-finite values such as NaN, infinity, or negative
infinity.

\c DakotaFloat is an \c Annotated float with a custom serializer.  During
JSON serialization:

<ul>
<li>finite values remain numeric,</li>
<li>NaN becomes \c "nan",</li>
<li>positive infinity becomes \c "inf", and</li>
<li>negative infinity becomes \c "-inf".</li>
</ul>

This keeps exported JSON schema and serialized model data compatible with
the downstream C++ handling used by %Dakota.  In general, if an existing
field in %Dakota grammar can use sentinel floating-point values such as
\c DBL_MAX, \c -DBL_MAX, or infinity-like defaults, prefer \c DakotaFloat.

*/

} // namespace Dakota
